text: :joy: the new status logging is stressing me out
should quiet down after the initial bump
<@UEFG14S5A> has joined the channel
<@U28TLDP0R> can you plz get <@UEFG14S5A> access to our github plz
<@UEFG14S5A> can you send me your github username, and also your ip address so that I can give you access to the dev/uncached website?
yup, it's `gbateman` and my ip address is 65.92.68.92
okay let me set up a few more things before I dump the wall of info on you
our build process is kinda overly complicated but I’m trying to strip away as much as possible since what you’ll be working on is pure javascript
can you see a webpage when you go to <http://dev.edhrec.com/commanders/ulrich-of-the-krallenhorde> ?
yup
excellent

so this might seem strange, but I think this setup should provide you what you need.  our dev setup isn’t very friendly and is something I’d like to improve, but it’s hard to find the time for.  but anyway, some background info:

<http://edhrec.com|edhrec.com> is served through cloudfront and is mostly cached, but <http://dev.edhrec.com|dev.edhrec.com> is direct to our box in AWS.  so if you made some changes, they will be available immediately in dev. but could take up to 24 hours to reach <http://edhrec.com|edhrec.com>

currently, every webpage on edhrec is built separately and served by nginx, which is great for performance but very bad when you want to push out an update to every page.  usually takes another 24 hours or so.

unfortunately we don’t currently have a dedicated development box, so usually when I’m writing new code I test it on dev, and make sure I don’t leave anything broken up for 24+ hours else it will make its way into the cached website

so instead of worrying about all that, I’ve created a separate repo for you, containing a single .js file.  if you push stuff to that file, it will get executed on <http://dev.edhrec.com|dev.edhrec.com> but it won’t get pushed to live.
oh ok, so both are sourced from the same box, just dev is never cached and <http://edhrec.com|edhrec.com> is
well <http://edhrec.com|edhrec.com> gets all its data from <http://dev.edhrec.com|dev.edhrec.com>
makes sense

and the separate repo file is cool - there were some parts of the specs, like giving recommendations, that would require interacting with the backend more directly than a js file that gets executed on load
any ideas how that could work with this setup?
ah okay, so for that I’d probably just make a json endpoint that you can use
you might even be able to use the deckstats endpoint, I’ll have to take inventory.  but setting up a new one would be easy as well
I can do the endpoint as well
by the way, currently Ulrich is the only page that’s reading the js file, but it should be on the whole website in about 24 hours
Keattz how about we set up a dummy page thats a copy of ulrich
Then he can do whatever
shouldn’t matter, the js only is imported on dev.
nobody on <http://edhrec.com|edhrec.com> will see it
Ooh thats cool
one step closer to a real dev box :stuck_out_tongue:
So that I can test locally without needing to push code for every iteration, can I assume that this file is simply executed on page load?
yeah
in the final product it will just be part of our js bundle

also, edhrec uses scryfall to for images, and another one of the specs requests images for the cards in the list - it doesn't seem entirely efficient to call scryfall's API and parse it on the front end, but if this is to exist entirely on the front end I'm not sure of a better way - any ideas?
card pricing also has this issue ^
Can you pull the info you need from the main site since its there?
From the main pages dom

With how the extension currently works, the list is persisted in localstorage so that they can access their list from whichever of the sites pages they're on - this means the data isn't always available, but if it was limited page by page then it would be
For example, they could go on Augustine IV's page and add some cards, then go to the Azorius page and add some more cards and they would add to the same list
I guess what im suggesting is you presist that stuff when its added
Oh, yeah that makes sense, that definitely works
also there’s a json object on each page (json_dict, near bottom) with scryfall images and prices and such
so if it helps you can just copy entries out of that and store those in the session
Is that on every page tho
Like on sets pages etc
yeah
Cool
if it’s a list of cards, it’s from json_dict
How about the commander at the top
that one isn’t
I could throw it in there though
Hmm if we put a button on the cards to add it to the clip board... we can put shit in that?

Adding commander to the dict would help a lot - one of the major concerns I had when making the extension is how tightly coupled the layout of the site is to buttons and card data, so having buttons added by default and having data in json_dict is good

so the lists of cards are built by our js bundle.  if you disable js and look at one of our webpages, there will be no lists of cards.  I’ll try to figure out a good way to give you access to that as well.

oh, another thing I thought of - I need a way to add styles for the elements I'm adding - I can do this purely in js but it would be easier for me if there were a way to include some variant of a css file
ah yeah, I’ll probably just do the same thing with a css file
we use es6 and less for js and css, so if you’d prefer to write in those that’s fine
I have an idea for getting you the cardlist.js code in a way you can mess with it, but I need to afk for a bit
btw <https://edhrec.com/commanders> exists
